CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved The CIU has identified the sidewalk left in asphalt as belonging to National Grid.     Utility companies are required to restore the sidewalk to original condition within 60 days of completion of their temporary work.     Because we are in the winter moratorium season of concrete/brick work (November 15-April 15)  the restoration work will be held off until next spring.     The utility company has been notified that the repairs must take place next April.      The location has been entered into the CIU data base that tracks repairs to be made by utility companies or private contractors.    The CIU will remind the utility companies next April about their obligation to restore the sidewalks within 2 weeks of the 2014 construction season.    Mark Cardarelli  Supervisor of Utility Coordination and Compliance  Boston Public Works Department  617-635-4951 Office  617-438-8517 Cell

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved The PWD Roadway Repair Contractor is working on your street performing patch paving.    It is an important city service for your neighborhood to provide the best permanent repairs of previous utility excavations or potholes.    The construction process is to dig out 6.5 inches of material and place 5 inches of dense binder hot mix asphalt in 2 lifts. The dense binder gives the patch its strength but is has large stones and is not conducive to providing a smooth ride  the contractor usually within a week comes back and places 1.5 inches of the top course. The top course is hot mix asphalt that provides the smooth ride.    The street is leafleted before the work begins where it explains that it is a mufti phase construction operation and you should look at the dates since they will change as each construction phases progresses.    Our goal is to allow parking between phases and not post the street for the entire time the work takes place. This is why the contractor repeatedly changes the dates.    We spoke to the contractor about his need to be totally accurate when posting for upcoming work.    Since this is a patching contract  the contractor may only be on your street for only a short period of time; giving the appearance of not showing up.    Sometimes poor weather  plant breakdowns  or equipment failure occurs which results in the delay of the upcoming work.    The CIU spoke to the contractor about his need to do a better job on changing the dates when those situations arise.    The street will be topped today.    The city apologizes for the inconvenience this necessary work has caused.    Sincerely      Mark Cardarelli  Supervisor of Utility Coordination and Compliance  Boston Public Works Department  617-635-4951 Office
SUBJECT: Public Works Department
Location: 772 E Sixth St  South Boston  MA  02127

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Noted I'm not sure which specific intersection you are requesting stop lines for  but we generally do not mark stop lines unless there is a marked crosswalk. This is because motorists will need to stop in advance of the crosswalk  which isn't always the 'natural' stopping point at an intersection. If motorists are rolling through the stop sign  they know it is there and painting a stop line will not change that behavior. Boston Police actively monitor and enforce stop sign violations.
